08775nam a22011295i 9783110631883DE-B159720230228123812.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20192019gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831106318837 a10.1515/97831106318832doi  a(DE-B1597)503136  a(OCoLC)1083583877  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE04a930qDE-101  aFE 4101qSEPA2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/30297:00aApproaches to Greek Poetry :bHomer, Hesiod, Pindar, and Aeschylus in Ancient Exegesis /ced. by Marco Ercoles, Lara Pagani, Filippomaria Pontani, Giuseppe Ucciardello. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (VI, 394 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTrends in Classics - Supplementary Volumes ,x1868-4785 ;v7300tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tPart I: Homeric exegesis in antiquity -- tObservations on Aristarchus’ Homeric studies -- tEratosthenes, Crates and Aristarchus on the Homeric dual. Rethinking the origins of the ‘analogy vs. anomaly controversy’ -- tChi -- tGlossary to Odyssey VIII in a new papyrus fragment from the Leipzig Papyrus- und Ostrakasammlung -- tPart II: Homeric and Hesiodic exegesis in Byzantine manuscripts and texts -- tThe Iliad “Textscholien” in the Venetus A -- tThe oldest textual witness of John Tzetzes’ Exegesis of the Iliad -- tOn the sources of Lascaris’ edition of the D-scholia on the Iliad -- tEnumerating the Muses: Tzetzes in Hes. Op. 1 and the parody of catalogic poetry in Epicharmus -- tPart III: Pindar between scholia and lexica -- tAristarchomastix. Dionysius of Sidon between epic and lyric poetry -- tTheon’s Pindaric exegesis: new materials from marginalia on papyri -- tCriticism of Pindar’s poetry in the scholia vetera -- tA lexicographical collection in two manuscripts of Cyrillus’ Lexicon and a new testimonium on Pindar -- tPart IV: Aeschylus in the exegetical tradition -- tThe imaginative poet: Aeschylus’ phantasiai in ancient literary criticism -- tAeschylus’ scholia in ms. Ath. Iber. 209: Two examples -- tAround Europe in two hundred years: The wanderings of ms. Ath. Iber. 209 -- tAfterword -- tAncient Scholarship Today -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex nominum et rerum -- tIndex locorum0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the last decades the field of research on ancient Greek scholarship has been the object of a remarkable surge of interest, with the publication of handbooks, reference works, and new editions of texts. This partly unexpected revival is very promising and it continues to enhance and modify both our knowledge of ancient scholarship and the way in which we are accustomed to discuss these texts and tackle the editorial and exegetical challenges they pose. This volume deals with some pivotal aspects of this topic, being the outcome of a three-year project funded by the Italian Ministry for Education, University and Research (MIUR) on specific aspects of the critical re-appraisal of Homer, Hesiod, Pindar, and Aeschylus in Greek culture throughout antiquity and the Middle Ages. It tackles issues such as the material form of the transmission of the exegesis from papyri to codices, the examination of hitherto unexplored branches of the manuscript evidence, the discussion of some important scholia, and the role played by the indirect tradition and the assimilation of the exegetical heritage in grammatical and lexicographical works. Some strands of the ancient and medieval scholarship are here re-evaluated afresh by adopting an interdisciplinary methodology which blends modern editorial techniques developed for ‘problematic’ or ‘non-authorial’ medieval texts with current trends in the history of philology and literary criticism. In their diversity of subject matter and approach the papers collected in the volume give intended readers an excellent overview of the topics of the project.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 4aAeschylus. 4aHomer. 4aScholien. 4aÜberlieferungsgeschichte.  aGreek and Byzantine philology.  amanuscript tradition.  ascholia.1 aCardin, Marta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColomo, Daniela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErcoles, Marco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErcoles, Marco, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFera, Maria Cannatà, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFranchi, Caterina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMatthaios, Stephanos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeliadò, Claudio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMerro, Grazia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMontana, Fausto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMontanari, Franco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMuratore, Davide, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNünlist, René, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPagani, Lara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPagani, Lara, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPontani, Filippomaria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPontani, Filippomaria, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTosi, Renzo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTribulato, Olga, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aUcciardello, Giuseppe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vo